3.3.3 Changes in the ocean interior
Figure 11 shows the vertical distributions of modeled
changes between years 1765 and 2000 of some ocean proper-
ties. Although atmospheric temperature warms most at high
latitudes, ocean surface layer warming is greater at low-mid
latitudes since sea ice cover shields much of the high lat-
itude surface layer from heating and since intense vertical
mixing there resists surface layer change (Fig. 11a). How-
ever, the intense mixing also heats deeper layers faster at high
latitudes. The increased atmospheric water vapor transport
forces a saltier and a fresher surface layer in the low-mid
and high latitude sectors, respectively (Fig. 11b). The DIC
increase in Fig. 11c shows that the high latitude ocean also

