The increase in high-cloud amount is hypothesised to be due to the increased upward moisture transport over the western Pacific (Fig. S5) caused by the enhanced upward motion and increased convection. A unique feature of increased aerosol column burden is seen over New Guinea in Fig. 2, which is likely due to reduced rainfall there. Together with the ocean processes such as changes in surface currents and the zonal sea surface temperature (SST) gradient in the equatorial Pacific (not shown), the mechanism causing conditions like La Niña is consistent with the positive Bjerknes feedback (Bjerknes, 1969; Rädel et al., 2016) that explains how the El Niño–Southern Oscillation (ENSO) anomaly is reinforced.

